Here is the complete, unbroken, master walkthrough to take you from your running Linux Mint system all the way to a dual-booted Arch Linux configuration with GNOME, without using a physical USB drive.
------------------------------
## Phase 1: Set Up the Loopback ISO Mode inside Mint
We will configure your computer to boot an Arch Linux installation environment straight from your hard disk.

   1. Open your browser in Linux Mint and download the official Arch Linux ISO (archlinux-x86_64.iso).
   2. Open your files application and move that downloaded ISO file into your primary Home folder.
   3. Rename the file exactly to: archlinux.iso
   4. Open your Terminal application and open your custom boot file:
   
   sudo nano /etc/grub.d/40_custom
   
   5. Use your arrow keys to scroll to the very bottom of the file. Paste this exact configuration block (replace yourusername with your actual Mint username):
   
   menuentry "Arch Linux Loopback ISO" {
       set isofile="/home/yourusername/archlinux.iso"
       loopback loop (hd0,gpt2)$isofile
       linux (loop)/arch/boot/x86_64/vmlinuz-linux img_dev=/dev/sda2 img_loop=$isofile copytoram
       initrd (loop)/arch/boot/x86_64/initramfs-linux.img
   }
   
   6. Save and exit the editor by pressing Ctrl + O, then Enter, then Ctrl + X.
   7. Update your system's boot records:
   
   sudo update-grub
   
   
------------------------------
## Phase 2: Boot and Prep Your Drive (CLI Resizing)
Since we are bypassing a USB, your system will load the entire Arch setup environment straight into your computer's RAM (copytoram), unlocking your hard drive for shrinking.

   1. Restart your Dell OptiPlex desktop.
   2. When the blue Dell logo appears, immediately tap the Esc key repeatedly (or press and hold Shift) to reveal the GRUB choice screen.
   3. Arrow down to choose "Arch Linux Loopback ISO" and press Enter.
   4. Once the text stops scrolling and you see the root@archiso ~ # command prompt, verify your hard disk is completely unmounted:
   
   umount /dev/sda2
   
   5. Launch the terminal partition manager for your A-Data SSD:
   
   parted /dev/sda
   
   6. Type p and hit Enter to display your current partitions. You will see partition 2 (/dev/sda2), which is your 233 GB Linux Mint space.
   7. Shrink the partition by giving it a new end boundary. Since you want to leave 14.9 GB of unallocated free space at the very end of your 238 GB disk, type:
   
   resizepart 2 223GB
   
   8. Type q and hit Enter to exit parted. You now have your 14.9 GB of raw space ready for Arch.

------------------------------
## Phase 3: Connect to Wi-Fi
You need a working internet connection to build the system.

   1. Launch the network control prompt:
   
   iwctl
   
   2. Run these configuration steps internally to pair with your router:
   
   station wlp2s0 scan
   station wlp2s0 get-networks
   station wlp2s0 connect YOUR_WIFI_NAME
   
   (Type out your Wi-Fi password when prompted).
   3. Type exit to return to the core prompt. Verify internet connectivity by running:
   
   ping -c 3 google.com
   
   
------------------------------
## Phase 4: Run the Automated Installer

   1. Initialize the guided setup wizard:
   
   archinstall
   
   2. Configure the following critical fields inside the terminal UI menu using your arrow keys and spacebar:
   * Disk configuration:
      1. Choose Manual partitioning.
         2. Select your main A-Data SSD drive (/dev/sda).
         3. Drop down to the Free Space row at the bottom. Select Create Partition, assign it all available space, mark the filesystem as ext4, and set the Mountpoint to /.
         4. Go to /dev/sda1 (your existing 511MB Mint EFI partition). Select it, assign its Mountpoint to /boot, and ensure you DO NOT select the format option.
         5. Select Save and Exit.
      * Profile: Select Desktop, then select GNOME.
      * Audio: Choose Pipewire.
      * Bootloader: Select GRUB.
      * Network configuration: Select Use NetworkManager.
      * User account: Create your username and password. Crucially, check the box that grants your user Sudo/Administrator rights.
   3. Scroll to the bottom and select Install. This process will take roughly 5 to 10 minutes.

------------------------------
## Phase 5: Deep Space Cleaning (Safety Net)
Before loading into your new desktop environment, you must prune GNOME's bloated default applications to keep your 14.9 GB boundary safe.

   1. When the installation concludes, the script will prompt: "Would you like to chroot into the newly installed system?" Type yes and hit Enter.
   2. Wipe out heavy, non-essential GNOME native software:
   
   pacman -Rns gnome-weather gnome-maps gnome-music gnome-contacts gnome-tour gnome-photos epiphany
   
   3. Establish an automatic script to continuously purge old setup file downloads:
   
   pacman -S pacman-contrib
   systemctl enable paccache.timer
   
   4. Set a permanent strict ceiling on system logs so they never consume more than 50MB:
   
   echo "SystemMaxUse=50M" >> /etc/systemd/journald.conf
   
   5. Exit the chroot backend framework and reboot your hardware:
   
   exit
   reboot
   
   
When your system boots back up, you will see a unified menu listing Arch Linux and Linux Mint side-by-side.
